<ns0:eml xmlns:ns0="eml://ecoinformatics.org/eml-2.1.0" xmlns:ns2="http://www.xml-cml.org/schema/stmml-1.1" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" packageId="knb-lter-cce.152.3" scope="system" system="knb" xsi:schemaLocation="eml://ecoinformatics.org/eml-2.1.0 http://oceaninformatics.ucsd.edu/docs/schemas/eml-2.1.0/eml.xsd"><access authSystem="knb" order="allowFirst" scope="document"><allow><principal>uid=CCE,o=lter,dc=ecoinformatics,dc=org</principal><permission>all</permission></allow><allow><principal>public</principal><permission>read</permission></allow></access><dataset scope="document"><shortName>Secchi Disk Depth Onshore and Offshore - Annual Average</shortName><title>Mean annual Secchi depth measurements in the period starting in1969 provide a measure of water column transparency in the CalCOFI inshore and offshore areas.</title><creator scope="document"><organizationName>California Current Ecosystem Long-Term Ecological Research Program</organizationName><individualName><givenName>Mark</givenName><surName>Ohman</surName></individualName><positionName>Current originator</positionName></creator><keywordSet><keyword>Habitat marine</keyword><keyword>Measurements radiation</keyword><keyword>Southern California Bight</keyword><keyword>Eastern Boundary Current</keyword><keyword>Habitat marine</keyword><keyword>LTER</keyword><keyword>San Diego</keyword><keyword>Southern California Bight</keyword></keywordSet><intellectualRights><para>Citation acknowledgement: Data from the California Current Ecosystem LTER data repository were supported by funding sources</para></intellectualRights><distribution scope="document"><online><url function="information">http://oceaninformatics.ucsd.edu/datazoo/data/all/datasets?action=summary&amp;id=152</url></online></distribution><contact scope="document"><individualName><givenName>James</givenName><surName>Conners</surName></individualName><positionName>information manager</positionName><address scope="document"><deliveryPoint>University of California, San Diego</deliveryPoint><deliveryPoint>Scripps Institution of Oceanography</deliveryPoint><deliveryPoint>Integrative Oceanography Department (IOD)</deliveryPoint><deliveryPoint>9500 Gilman Dr.</deliveryPoint><city>La Jolla</city><administrativeArea>CA</administrativeArea><postalCode>92093-0218</postalCode><country>USA</country></address></contact><publisher scope="document"><organizationName>California Current Ecosystem LTER</organizationName><onlineUrl>http://cce.lternet.edu/</onlineUrl></publisher><methods><methodStep><description><section><title>abstract</title><para>The Secchi depth provides a measure of water turbidity.  Measurements are made as part of the California Fisheries Cooperative Investigations (CalCOFI). Secchi depth is measured on each station on each cruise. The mean annual is obtained by averaging stations over time and at stations defined as either inshore or offshore.</para></section></description></methodStep><methodStep><description><section><title>methods</title><para>The Secchi disk (originally Secchi disc) is deployed on a hydrowire with a weight on the bottom. The disk is a completely white, circular metal disk. A Secchi cast is done in conjunction with each station either before or after the CTD cast. The disk is lowered through the water column until it disappears and then raised slowly. The depth at which it is visible again is recorded as the secchi depth. Light penetration is sometimes estimated from the Secchi depth; that is, frequestly the 1% light level is estimated to be three times the Secchi depth.</para></section></description></methodStep><sampling><studyExtent><coverage scope="document"><temporalCoverage scope="document"><rangeOfDates><beginDate><calendarDate>1969-01-01</calendarDate></beginDate><endDate><calendarDate>2004-01-01</calendarDate></endDate></rangeOfDates></temporalCoverage></coverage><coverage scope="document"><geographicCoverage scope="document"><geographicDescription>Sampling takes place west of California. Sampling arrangements include use of the CalCOFI fixed grid of stations located within the Southern California Bight along offshore transects from San Diego to Point Conception and use of moving stations centered on drifters or drogues.</geographicDescription><boundingCoordinates><westBoundingCoordinate>-124.323</westBoundingCoordinate><eastBoundingCoordinate>-117.305381</eastBoundingCoordinate><northBoundingCoordinate>35.088243</northBoundingCoordinate><southBoundingCoordinate>29.846372</southBoundingCoordinate></boundingCoordinates><datasetGPolygon><datasetGPolygonOuterGRing><gRingPoint><gRingLatitude>35.088243</gRingLatitude><gRingLongitude>-124.323</gRingLongitude></gRingPoint><gRingPoint><gRingLatitude>29.846372</gRingLatitude><gRingLongitude>-124.323</gRingLongitude></gRingPoint><gRingPoint><gRingLatitude>29.846372</gRingLatitude><gRingLongitude>-117.305381</gRingLongitude></gRingPoint><gRingPoint><gRingLatitude>35.088243</gRingLatitude><gRingLongitude>-117.305381</gRingLongitude></gRingPoint></datasetGPolygonOuterGRing></datasetGPolygon></geographicCoverage></coverage></studyExtent><samplingDescription><section><title>Geographic Description</title><para>The CalCOFI inshore area is defined in Aksnes et al. (2007) as within approx. 150 km of the coast. The CalCOFI offshore area corresponds to the subareas 10-15 defined in Aksnes et al. (2007), that is approximately 450-750 km off the coast.</para></section></samplingDescription></sampling></methods><project scope="document"><title>California Current Ecosystem Long-Term Ecological Research Program</title><personnel scope="document"><individualName><givenName>James</givenName><surName>Conners</surName></individualName><address scope="document"><deliveryPoint>University of California, San Diego</deliveryPoint><deliveryPoint>Scripps Institution of Oceanography</deliveryPoint><deliveryPoint>Integrative Oceanography Department (IOD)</deliveryPoint><deliveryPoint>9500 Gilman Dr.</deliveryPoint><city>La Jolla</city><administrativeArea>CA</administrativeArea><postalCode>92093-0218</postalCode><country>USA</country></address><role>information manager</role></personnel><personnel scope="document"><individualName><givenName>Mark</givenName><surName>Ohman</surName></individualName><address scope="document"><deliveryPoint>University of California, San Diego</deliveryPoint><deliveryPoint>Scripps Institution of Oceanography</deliveryPoint><deliveryPoint>Integrative Oceanography Department (IOD)</deliveryPoint><deliveryPoint>9500 Gilman Dr.</deliveryPoint><city>La Jolla</city><administrativeArea>CA</administrativeArea><postalCode>92093-0218</postalCode><country>USA</country></address><role>principal investigator</role></personnel><abstract><para>The California Current Ecosystem program  is a member site of the Long-Term Ecological Research program, a network of sites investigating diverse biomes.  A team of researchers is investigating nonlinear transitions in the California Current coastal pelagic ecosystem, with particular attention to long-term forcing by a secular warming trend, the Pacific Decadal Oscillation, and El Nino in altering the structure and dynamics of the pelagic ecosystem. The California Current System is a coastal upwelling biome, as found along the eastern margins of all major ocean basins. These are among the most productive ecosystems in the world ocean. The California Current sustains active fisheries for a variety of finfish and marine invertebrates, modulates weather patterns and the hydrologic cycle of much of the western United States, and plays a vital role in the economy of myriad coastal communities.</para></abstract><funding><para>NSF/GEO/OCE-0417616</para></funding></project><dataTable scope="document"><entityName>datasetdatatable</entityName><attributeList><attribute scope="document"><attributeName>col_2819</attributeName><attributeLabel>Year</attributeLabel><attributeDefinition>year of measurement in GMT</attributeDefiniti